ttish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Willey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a pet form of the personal name   Will  , a short form of   William  . In some instances a variant of   Wiley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German   Willi  .","History: Isaac Willey is recorded in Boston, MA, in 1640, and went on to be one of the founders of New London, CT. His descendent Samuel Hopkins Willey (1821–1914) was one of the founders of the College of California at Berkeley in 1860."],"variants":[{"name":"Willie","meanings":["English: variant of   Willey  .","Scottish: variant of   Wylie  .","Native American (e.g. Navajo and Seminole): adoption of the English personal name <i>Willie</i> (pet form of   William  ) as a surname."]},{"name":"Will","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Will</i>, a short form of   William  . This surname is now commonly found in Scotland, in Aberdeenshire, Angus, and Kincardineshire.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring or stream, from Middle English <i>wel</i>, <i>wel(l)e</i>, <i>wille</i>, in a southwestern dialect form. This surname is found predominantly in the south and southwestern parts of the country. Compare   Well   1.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>iwil</i>, <i>wil(l)e</i> ‘agreeable, pleasing’."]},{"name":"Willy","meanings":["English: variant of   Willey  .","Americanized form of German   Willi  ."]}]},{"name":"Andreas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The original New Testament Greek form of   Andrew  , used in the English-speaking world as a learned variant."],"variants":[{"name":"Andries","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Andreas De Willey was born in 1230, in Willey, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Warrin De Willey, was 30 and his mother, Petronella Fitz Odo, de Kenley, was 26. He had at least 1 daughter with Grace Hungerford. He died on 24 August 1265, in his hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1230–24 August 1265":"1230–24. august 1265","1230–1265":"1230–1265","1225–1261":"1225–1261","1245–1331":"1245–1331","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","Abt 1245":"umbes 1245","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","1261":"1261","24 August 1265":"24. august 1265","Stourton, Wiltshire, England":"Stourton, Wiltshire, England","Willey, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Willey, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Probably Willey, Salop, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, England","Willey, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1230–24 August 1265":"1230–24. elokuuta 1265","1230–1265":"1230–1265","1225–1261":"1225–1261","1245–1331":"1245–1331","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1204–Female":"1204–Kuollut","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","Abt 1245":"noin 1245","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1331":"1331","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","12